The Official Rating: 4.8 / 5 Stars

If I had to describe the experience of reading this in one word, it would be "suffocating", but in the best possible way.

Reading this feels like standing in the middle of a lightning storm. You have the "Vajra" (the Thunderbolt) at the center, and you can feel the ozone in the air. 
It’s a story that doesn't let you breathe because the moment you step out of a life-or-death battlefield, you are thrust into a high-stakes emotional minefield.
There is a chilling contrast in how the lead character is written. One moment, he is a "death sentence" to an entire army, and the next, he is someone who notices the way a woman’s boots drag when she’s tired. It feels deeply protective. As a reader, you feel safe when he’s on the page, but you also feel a constant, low-thrumming dread because you know he’s carrying a secret that could break everything he’s trying to protect.
I felt a heavy ache reading about the "nameless" soldiers and the families waiting at home. The author doesn't treat war like a game of chess; they treat it like a tragedy where even the "winner" loses something. It made me look at the news differently. It’s rare to find a book that makes you root for a military victory while simultaneously mourning the cost of a single loaf of bread in an enemy city.
When I finished these chapters, I felt like I had been through a war myself—but I immediately wanted to go back to the front lines. It’s a book for anyone who likes their heroes complex, their stakes global hard-earned scenes.

It’s a story about the heavy price of being a shield for a nation.
